<br>
Disney has destroyed a number of historic pieces of literature or legend by making movies about it and Disneyifying it:<br>
<br>
- The Hunchback of Notre Dame<br>
- Beauty and the Beast<br>
- Pocahontas<br>
<br>
The story in each of these was fundamentally changed by Disney.  And as noted above, most people don't read books any more.  Childred will grow up thinking that the Hunchback was a cuddly guy, or that the whole Pocahontas story dealt with some bad breaks that some white folk got (or that Pocahontas was an adult).<br>
<br>
Mercifully, the LotR movies haven't horribly bastardized the books, presumably because it wasn't Disney doing the movies.  It still saddens me to think that there will be a generation growing up that probably won't read the books because they've seen the movie.  After all, why read and think when you can sit like a potted plant and stare at a screen...  that's the modern mantra for life isn't it? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fogelxanedu>Fogel Xanedu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Riding the Planes</span><br>  Posts: 702<br> <font color=#628CBC>(12/22/02 11:09:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=337.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   .</span><hr size=1> I'm a potted plant and I'm enjoying every moment of it. Ignorance is bliss.<br>
